[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 7/100 path 3/5 answer="Let \\( t \\) represent the time it takes for Lee to run the 400-meter hurdles before the diet change. According to the problem:\n\\[ t = 38 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nLee was originally able to run the race two seconds faster than Gerald:\n\\[ t + 2 = \\text{Gerald's original time} \\]\nThus,\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's original time} = t + 2 = 38 + 2 = 40 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nAfter changing his diet, Gerald’s speed improved by 10%, meaning he now runs the race at 90% of his original speed:\n\\[ \\text{Gerald's improved time} = \\frac{\\text{Gerald's original time}}{1.10} = \\frac{40}{1.10} \\]\n\nNow we calculate the time it took for Gerald to complete the race with his improved speed:\n\\[\n\\text{Gerald's improved time} = \\frac{40}{1.10} \\approx 36.36 \\text{ seconds}\n\\]\n\nTherefore, with his improved diet, Gerald can run the 400-meter hurdles approximately in **36.36 seconds**."
