[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 1/5 answer="Let's denote the total number of steps Elliott took during his walks to and from school as \\( S \\). According to the problem, he finished half of his steps on these walks, so we have:\n\n\\[ S / 2 \\]\n\nHe then walked an additional 1,000 steps with his friend. So the total steps taken before the jog would be:\n\n\\[ S / 2 + 1000 \\]\n\nAfter his short jog, he had 2,000 steps remaining. This means before jogging, he had 2,000 steps less than what he had after the jog, which gives us:\n\n\\[ (S / 2 + 1000) - 2000 \\]\n\nSince he started with the full 10,000 steps, we can set up the equation:\n\n\\[ 10000 = (S / 2 + 1000) - 2000 \\]\n\nNow let's solve this equation to find out how many steps he took during his jog.\n\nFirst, simplify the right side of the equation:\n\n\\[ 10000 = S / 2 + 1000 - 2000 \\]\n\\[ 10000 = S / 2 - 1000 \\]\n\nNext, add 1000 to both sides:\n\n\\[ 11000 = S / 2 \\]\n\nFinally, multiply both sides by 2 to find \\( S \\):\n\n\\[ 22000 = S \\]\n\nSo Elliott took 22,000 steps in total including the steps he took while walking to and from school, walking with his friend, and the short jog.\n\nTo find out how many steps he took during his jog, subtract the known steps taken without the jog from the"
