[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 start id=gsm8k_test_1022
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 1/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 1/5 answer='12'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 2/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 2/5 answer='Let \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold, and let \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals sold.\n\nFrom the problem statement:\n1. The cost of each small stuffed animal (\\( C_S \\)) is $4.\n2. Teresa sold small stuffed animals at triple the rate of large stuffed animals, so \\( C_L = 3C_S \\).\n3. The total earnings are $120.\n4. She sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones, thus \\( S = 2L \\).\n\nWe can set up equations based on these points:\n\nTotal earnings equation:\n\\[ C_S \\times S + C_L \\times L = 120 \\]\n\nSubstitute the values and relationships into the equation:\n\n\\[ 4S + (3 \\times 4)L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 4S + 12L = 120 \\]\n\nAnd we know from the relationship between small and large stuffed animals:\n\\[ S = 2L \\]\n\nNow substitute \\( S = 2L \\):\n\n\\[ 4(2L) + 12L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 8L + 12L = 120 \\]\n\\[ 20L = 120 \\]\n\nDivide both sides by 20 to solve for \\( L \\):\n\\[ L = \\frac{120}{20} \\]\n\\[ L = 6 \\]\n\nTherefore, Teresa sold 6 large stuffed animals.\n\nTo find the number of small stuffed animals:\n\\[ S = 2L \\]\n\\[ S = 2 \\times 6 \\]\n\\[ S = 12 \\]\n\nThus, Teresa sold 12 small stuffed animals.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 3/5 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 3/5 answer='Let \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold, and let \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals sold. We know two things:\n\n1. Each small stuffed animal costs $4.\n2. Teresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones, so \\( S = 2L \\).\n\nTeresa also knows that each large stuffed animal costs \\( \\frac{S}{3} \\) because it’s three times the price of a small one.\n\nFrom the first point about selling sizes:\n\\[ 4S = \\text{Total revenue from small stuffed animals} \\]\n\nAnd since \\( S = 2L \\), we can substitute:\n\\[ 4(2L) = \\text{Total revenue from small stuffed animals} \\]\n\\[ 8L = \\text{Total revenue from small stuffed animals} \\]\n\nSince the total revenue from all stuffed animals is $120:\n\\[ 8L + (\\frac{S}{3})L = 120 \\]\n\nSubstituting \\( S = 2L \\):\n\\[ 8L + \\frac{2L}{3} = 120 \\]\n\nTo solve for \\( L \\), multiply everything by 3 to clear fractions:\n\\[ 24L + 2L = 360 \\]\n\\[ 26L = 360 \\]\n\\[ L = \\frac{360}{26} \\]\n\\[ L = 13.846 \\]\n\nSince the number of items sold must be whole numbers, verify if these calculations fit real-world constraints. Since it seems like there might have been a miscalculation or misunderstanding. Let us revisit with correct steps:\n\nGiven:\n- Cost per small stuffed animal = $4\n- Total earnings = $120\n- Number of large stuffed animals sold ='
