[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 2/5 answer='Let \\( J \\) represent the total number of jellyfish in the tank. According to the problem:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{J}{5} \\text{ (large jellyfish)} + \\frac{\\frac{J}{5}}{3} \\text{ (small jellyfish)} = 6 \\text{ jellyfish}\n\\]\n\nSimplifying the equation:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{J}{5} + \\frac{J}{15} = 6\n\\]\n\nCombining the fractions:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{3J + J}{15} = 6 \\\\\n\\frac{4J}{15} = 6\n\\]\n\nMultiplying both sides by 15:\n\n\\[\n4J = 90\n\\]\n\nDividing both sides by 4:\n\n\\[\nJ = 22.5\n\\]\n\nSince the number of jellyfish must be a whole number, we recognize there might have been an error because \\( J \\) should be an integer. Let’s recheck if our initial assumptions were correct or if there was a misunderstanding.\n\nGiven the context and constraints, let’s consider rounding down:\nIf \\( J = 22 \\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{22}{5} = 4.4 \\quad (\\text{large jellyfish})\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{4.4}{3} = 1.4667 \\quad (\\text{small jellyfish})\n\\]\nAdding these up gives approximately \\( 4 + 1 = 5 \\), which is close but not matching the given condition of 6.\n\nRounding up would lead to \\( J = 23 \\):\n\n\\[\n\\frac{23}{5} = 4.6 \\quad (\\text{large jellyfish})\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{4.6}{3} = 1'
